<DOC><DOCNO> AP880429-0287 </DOCNO><FILEID>AP-NR-04-29-88 1448EDT</FILEID><FIRST>u f BC-Dollar-Gold     04-29 0320</FIRST><SECOND>BC-Dollar-Gold,0335</SECOND><HEAD>Dollar Higher, Gold Down</HEAD><DATELINE>LONDON (AP) </DATELINE><TEXT>   The dollar rose against most major currencies inEurope on Friday, reflecting a belief among traders that theAmerican economy is strengthening and U.S. interest rates arerising. Gold prices fell.   Foreign exchange dealers said the announcement that the MarchU.S. index of leading indicators rose 0.8 percent, together withother signs of upturn, gave a positive picture of the U.S. economy.   They said the announcement that the Riggs National Bank ofWashington increased its prime lending rate to 8.75 percent from8.5 percent further convinced the market that U.S. interest ratesare rising. Higher interest rates make the dollar more attractiveto foreigners.   The day's dramatic moves appeared in British sterling trading,following the announcement of better-than-expected British tradedata. Dealers said the Bank of England intervened to smooth thepound's rise.   Britain's merchandise trade deficit narrowed unexpectedly inMarch to a seasonally adjusted $1.61 billion from $2.48 billion inFebruary, the government said Friday.   In late trading, the pound was quoted at $1.8785, slightly moreexpensive for buyers than $1.8755 late Thursday.   Other dollar rates in Europe late Friday compared with lateThursday included: 1.6725 West German marks, up from 1.6705; 1.3910Swiss francs, up from 1.3832; 5.6805 French francs, up from 5.6685;1.8745 Dutch guilders, up from 1.8715; 1,242.00 Italian lire, upfrom 1,240.50; 1.2280 Canadian dollars, down from 1.22965.   Japanese markets were closed for Emperor Hirohito's birthday.The dollar was quoted at 124.80 yen in London, fractionally downfrom 124.82 yen at the close of business Thursday in Tokyo.   Gold prices in London late Friday were quoted at a price of$449.25 a troy ounce, down from $451 late Thursday.   In Zurich, gold was bid at $449.00, down from $452.00.   Earlier, gold closed in Hong Kong at a bid $451.17, down from$453.54.   Silver bullion was quoted in London at a bid $6.45, down from$6.50.</TEXT></DOC>